<br>
How I would modify it... take however many pork chops you need, either thin, regular or thick cut. Boneless or not as you prefer (bones add flavor, but they're annoying lol).<br>
<br>
season lightly with pepper, thyme, and garlic powder... (normally would also do salt, but...)<br>
<br>
Brown on both sides in vegetable or olive oil (just enough to keep them from sticking)<br>
<br>
Leave them in the pan on low or turned off while you mix together a can of low sodium cream of mushroom soup, half a soup can of water or white wine or grape juice, and a little more thyme and pepper.<br>
<br>
thinly slice half a small onion (I use a whole medium one, but my husband and I like onion lol) and scatter it over the pork chops. Pour the soup mixture over the top and simmer until pork chops are cooked through.<br>
<br>
am unsure of the exact amounts of sodium in that... but I do know that provided you don't go too heavy on the onion it won't aggrivate heartburn/acid reflux (as I suffer from that myself and hate every second of it) and it's not very spicy.<br>
<br>
Recipe can also be made with chicken breast, and it makes its own gravy thats very good over potatos 8) From time to time I've added an extra half cup of sliced raw mushrooms just for that extra mushroomy flavor lol.<br>
<br>
Another variation of it is to set up all the ingredients (raw) in a baking pan (8x8 is what I used but it was VERY crowded lol) and add in a couple of quartered and washed red skin potatos, then bake at 350 for about 30 minutes or until the potatos test as done<br>
<br>
Hmm... might be able to do light stir frys... I came up with a really good shrimp stir fry last month, but didn't write down the amounts of anything... basically it was an assortment of veggies (broccoli, carrots, zucchini, bok choy, green onions and snow peas), some shrimp, spices (as I recall I used garlic, 5 spice, and something green... was either chervil or parsley because I like the color), and the sauce was chicken stock, soy sauce, and corn starch<br>
<br>
think, if you go light on the soy sauce and use a low sodium chicken broth it would still be tasty... and veggies are healthy!<br>
<br>
